Hedge funds and other speculative investors have cut wagers on higher gold prices to their lowest level since July. Net bets on higher gold prices by hedge funds and other speculative investors fell by more than 50% during the week ended May 1, according to the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. The net bullish bets stayed near that level the following week.

The current price of gold appears to be comfortable trading under $1,300. So far weak demand from China and U.S. dollar valuation has dampen demand. Because gold is sensitive to world economic and political events there is always the possibility for a run up in price in reaction to one of these events. Since the unknown is, well, unknown one must always make some room in a prediction for such possibility. Baring that it will continue to languish in the $1250 - $1300 range.

Gold has seen a recent decline in price over past 2 weeks. Trend for these declines has been around 2-3 weeks. With current geopolitical uncertainty, investors likely to look for safer investments, but timing unlikely to reach above $1350 per ounce in next 6 weeks. Will reevaluate as time progresses.
